Rose '62 is flowing

00:42:41.050 --> 00:42:44.180
from machines previously
used at the Kimmelman bat

00:42:44.180 --> 00:42:47.330
mitzvah for chocolate dipping.

00:42:47.330 --> 00:42:49.754
And that is true.

00:42:49.754 --> 00:42:50.920
But this was a larger party.

00:42:50.920 --> 00:42:53.290
There were some normies there.

00:42:53.290 --> 00:42:55.800
Horrible joke.

00:42:55.800 --> 00:42:59.350
But it's actually very rare for
a lot of us, the right people

00:42:59.350 --> 00:43:01.220
to be in the room
at the same time.

00:43:01.220 --> 00:43:06.090
And there were 10 or 12 of us
gathered around a little circle

00:43:06.090 --> 00:43:08.020
with a lot of
other people trying

00:43:08.020 --> 00:43:10.090
to get in on the conversation.

00:43:10.090 --> 00:43:14.340
And myself and Jose Andreas
and Colicchio and Bobby Flay

00:43:14.340 --> 00:43:19.530
and Jean-Georges Vongerichten
and-- I'm blanking on some,

00:43:19.530 --> 00:43:22.200
but people like that.

00:43:22.200 --> 00:43:23.960
And we're all standing around.

00:43:23.960 --> 00:43:25.710
And the game that we
were actually playing

00:43:25.710 --> 00:43:29.960
was, who was cooking at
that restaurant in the '80s,

00:43:29.960 --> 00:43:33.100
because the '80s was a decade--
I completely forget the '80s.

00:43:33.100 --> 00:43:35.540
I'm a recovering alcoholic
and heroin addict,

00:43:35.540 --> 00:43:39.940
and that was the decade I didn't
sober up until January of '92.

00:43:39.940 --> 00:43:42.410
So I can't tell you a
thing about the '80s.

00:43:42.410 --> 00:43:45.050
When I married my wife, she
laughed because I'd never

00:43:45.050 --> 00:43:47.880
seen an episode of "Friends."

00:43:47.880 --> 00:43:48.540
It's true.

00:43:48.540 --> 00:43:51.480
I just missed the whole decade.

00:43:51.480 --> 00:43:52.944
So I was cooking
a lot in New York.

00:43:52.944 --> 00:43:54.360
And we're all
trying to figure out

00:43:54.360 --> 00:43:56.370
who-- we were all young
line cooks coming up.

00:43:56.370 --> 00:43:59.260
And we remember it like,
this guy was amazing.

00:43:59.260 --> 00:44:00.470
Whatever happened to him?

00:44:00.470 --> 00:44:02.180
He was such a better
cook than all of us.

00:44:02.180 --> 00:44:05.220
And it's odd how so
many of us were working

00:44:05.220 --> 00:44:08.120
in the same restaurants
at the time together

00:44:08.120 --> 00:44:10.690
or followed each other
when one person left.

00:44:10.690 --> 00:44:13.340
Because the world of line
cooks in New York back then

00:44:13.340 --> 00:44:14.950
was fairly finite.

00:44:14.950 --> 00:44:17.930
And it's amazing that so
many of us, now in our 50s,

00:44:17.930 --> 00:44:21.050
are kind of like elder statesmen
in a much more popular food

00:44:21.050 --> 00:44:22.220
universe.

00:44:22.220 --> 00:44:25.860
And at one point,
someone said oh,

00:44:25.860 --> 00:44:28.740
are you going to contribute to
such and such gala or whatever.

00:44:28.740 --> 00:44:35.080
And Tom Colicchio
got on his soapbox.

00:44:35.080 --> 00:44:39.540
And it was so motivating
and so inspiring to hear

00:44:39.540 --> 00:44:42.460
somebody-- I mean,
it's one thing for me

00:44:42.460 --> 00:44:43.710
to say it to you guys.

00:44:43.710 --> 00:44:46.830
But when I grab my colleagues,
I mean my real peers

00:44:46.830 --> 00:44:48.890
and colleagues by the
lapels, the ones who

00:44:48.890 --> 00:44:51.960
aren't playing the
game the right way,

00:44:51.960 --> 00:44:58.630
and convince them that fewer
galas, fewer fundraisers, fewer

00:44:58.630 --> 00:45:01.910
of everything, dedicate
all your resources

00:45:01.910 --> 00:45:06.860
to putting a million people
on the Mall in Washington, DC,

00:45:06.860 --> 00:45:12.690
insisting that our government
change its way of doing things

00:45:12.690 --> 00:45:18.060
and insisting on a national
food policy and a federal agency

00:45:18.060 --> 00:45:19.100
that would supervise it.

00:45:19.100 --> 00:45:20.860
I mean, those are
the kind of things

00:45:20.860 --> 00:45:24.360
that are really meaningful,
and that perhaps this was

00:45:24.360 --> 00:45:28.050
the year for all of us
to kind of, collectively,

00:45:28.050 --> 00:45:33.790
take a step back from
pissing in the wind.

00:45:33.790 --> 00:45:35.600
I'm still donating
as much as I can

00:45:35.600 --> 00:45:38.790
to my local food self,
because I can't not do that.

00:45:38.790 --> 00:45:41.670
But on the bigger,
grander scheme of things,

00:45:41.670 --> 00:45:44.050
taking some of the energy
that I've been doing that

00:45:44.050 --> 00:45:46.870
hasn't been making the change.

00:45:46.870 --> 00:45:48.690
Helps to throw a
nice party, and maybe

00:45:48.690 --> 00:45:50.950
focusing it on a couple
days on my schedule

00:45:50.950 --> 00:45:53.910
that I go to Capitol Hill
and I work hard on something.

00:45:53.910 --> 00:45:57.750
And it made sense to me, because
two years ago I got a phone

00:45:57.750 --> 00:46:00.160
call from the one organization.

00:46:00.160 --> 00:46:02.070
And they asked me to help.

00:46:02.070 --> 00:46:04.080
They wanted me to tell
stories about Africa

00:46:04.080 --> 00:46:05.796
and help electrify Africa.

00:46:05.796 --> 00:46:07.920
Because if you want to make
Africa safe and secure,

00:46:07.920 --> 00:46:09.336
how about giving
them electricity?

00:46:09.336 --> 00:46:11.440
But let's stop throwing
money over there.

00:46:11.440 --> 00:46:14.120
Let's stop supporting
tin pot dictators.

00:46:14.120 --> 00:46:16.150
Let's stop supporting oligarchs.

00:46:16.150 --> 00:46:19.760
Let's stop sending bags of
rice out of cargo planes.

00:46:19.760 --> 00:46:21.880
Let's just give them
electricity so the food

00:46:21.880 --> 00:46:25.760
that they grow and make
themselves can be stored.

00:46:25.760 --> 00:46:28.510
Let's give them electricity
so that when we give them

00:46:28.510 --> 00:46:31.040
medicines that are
perishable, they can have them

00:46:31.040 --> 00:46:33.210
in refrigerators that work.

00:46:33.210 --> 00:46:35.510
If you put electricity
in Namibia,

00:46:35.510 --> 00:46:39.620
it would become one of the
leading exporters in the world

00:46:39.620 --> 00:46:41.280
of fish and shellfish.

00:46:41.280 --> 00:46:45.130
The best seafood in the world
comes from the Skeleton Coast

00:46:45.130 --> 00:46:48.630
as it wraps around the Western
side of the Horn of Africa.

00:46:48.630 --> 00:46:51.380
The best in the world
comes from there.

00:46:51.380 --> 00:46:55.031
Not Spain, not New England,
not Australia, Namibia.

00:46:55.031 --> 00:46:55.530
Right?

00:46:55.530 --> 00:46:58.170
But they don't have electricity,
so they can't process the fish

00:46:58.170 --> 00:46:59.600
and seafood.

00:46:59.600 --> 00:47:02.380
I digress.

00:47:02.380 --> 00:47:08.640
If we can put
together the attention

00:47:08.640 --> 00:47:13.180
in the right way as we did with
the Electrify Africa campaign,

00:47:13.180 --> 00:47:17.600
and if the food people took a
page out of the social justice

00:47:17.600 --> 00:47:21.980
playbook that ONE has, solely
focusing on legislating issues

00:47:21.980 --> 00:47:24.030
one after another
after another, I

00:47:24.030 --> 00:47:25.870
think we would
have more success.

00:47:25.870 --> 00:47:27.930
So it really resonated with me.

00:47:27.930 --> 00:47:30.310
And we all sort of took
a blood oath that night

00:47:30.310 --> 00:47:32.960
that that was going
to be our focus.

00:47:32.960 --> 00:47:35.960
And I'm super, super proud
of that, because I've

00:47:35.960 --> 00:47:37.520
seen it work with ONE.

00:47:37.520 --> 00:47:38.880
So, anyway.

